I would split it like this:

modules/
  cloudsql-mysql/
    main.tf
    variables.tf
    outputs.tf

  cloudsql-postgresql/
    main.tf
    variables.tf
    outputs.tf

  cloudsql-sqlserver/
    main.tf
    variables.tf
    outputs.tf

Then keep a higher-level factory/orchestration layer:

modules/
  cloudsql-factory/
    main.tf
    variables.tf
Why this is better

Right now, one module has many conditions like:

startswith(var.database_version, "MYSQL")
startswith(var.database_version, "POSTGRES")
startswith(var.database_version, "SQLSERVER")

That works, but it becomes harder to maintain because MySQL, PostgreSQL, and SQL Server have different rules for:

backups
flags
password requirements
auditing
replicas
charset/collation
IAM authentication
SQL Server HA
PostgreSQL extensions
Recommended structure

Your factory module decides which child module to call:

module "mysql" {
  source = "../cloudsql-mysql"
  for_each = {
    for k, v in var.instances : k => v
    if startswith(v.database_version, "MYSQL")
  }

  name             = each.value.name
  project_id       = var.project_id
  database_version = each.value.database_version
}
module "postgresql" {
  source = "../cloudsql-postgresql"
  for_each = {
    for k, v in var.instances : k => v
    if startswith(v.database_version, "POSTGRES")
  }

  name             = each.value.name
  project_id       = var.project_id
  database_version = each.value.database_version
}
module "sqlserver" {
  source = "../cloudsql-sqlserver"
  for_each = {
    for k, v in var.instances : k => v
    if startswith(v.database_version, "SQLSERVER")
  }

  name             = each.value.name
  project_id       = var.project_id
  database_version = each.value.database_version
}
Best recommendation

Yes, split them into 3 modules, but do not duplicate everything.

Use shared/common pieces for:

naming
labels
networking
PSC
maintenance window
backup base variables
outputs

Then engine-specific modules handle only engine-specific behavior.

For example:

cloudsql-mysql       → MySQL flags, MySQL users, MySQL replicas
cloudsql-postgresql  → pgaudit, PostgreSQL flags, IAM auth, extensions
cloudsql-sqlserver   → root password required, no charset/collation, REGIONAL HA

